<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12073a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12073a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12073a"> 73(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 7 Rivermouths <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12073a"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Cardinal Moran <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> insisted rightly that the solution of the difficulty <font color="green">[i.e. the identification of Patrick&apos;s birthplace]</font> is to be found in the word Bonaven. Bon, or Ban, he tells us, is a Celtic word which signifies <mark>the mouth of a river</mark>, and Avon is the river itself. <small> William Canon Fleming, <a name="WFBS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WFBS"><cite title="source">Boulogne-sur-mer: St Patrick's native town</cite></a> (1907) 9</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The &lsquo;7&rsquo; may possibly derive, via Fleming page 10, where a theory is discussed which connects Bonaven with Bannaventa, from page 11: an entirely gratuitous assumption that there must have been a town named Bannaventa &ldquo;in the regions of the lower Severn.&rdquo;] </mm> </dd></dl>
